In this directory there are three different example of integraton of NVML call (to extract GPU enery) with fortran code.
* mm.F90: it is a Fortran program that performs naive dense matrix–matrix multiplication C = A*B for an n×n matrix size read from standard input.
It can run in CPU serial mode or GPU mode via OpenACC (single kernels region).
When compiled with NVML, it queries GPU energy usage (assumes exactly 4 GPUs: devices 0–3) before/after the kernel.
It reports runtime, MFLOPS, and per-GPU energy (J) / mean power (W), plus a simple result check value.
* sleep.F90: it is a minimal Fortran program demonstrating NVML-based GPU energy measurement.
After sleeping it samples energy again and computes per-GPU energy (J) and mean power (W) using elapsed time.
It also logs timestamps to time.log and uses timing_module for wall-clock timing.
* getEn: it is a simple Fortran program that returns the total energy (in Joule) consumed so far. 
It can be used as CLI in a job script to get pre/post Job Energy consumption. 


CAVEAT:
in this version it was tested noly using leonardo.

ACKNOWLEDGMENT:
The NVML wrapper was "Deeply Inspired" by Marco Lauricella's work (lauricella.marco@gmail.com). Thanks!



